text: March 17th is st. Patrick's Day
this holiday originated in Ireland but
it has become a very popular American
holiday as well
now many Americans themselves have Irish
roots but whether you're Irish or not
it's still a fun holiday to celebrate
I'd like to share a few expressions
connected to Saint Patrick's Day a
symbol of Ireland is the Shamrock it's a
three leaf clover many see the Shamrock
as a symbol of good luck in English we
have many idioms and expressions about
luck one that I like and one that I
think is very useful is as luck would
have it it's a way of explaining how
things happened how things turned out
example Jennifer was sorry that she had
to stop her Portuguese lessons after
only one year as luck would have it her
new neighbor is from Brazil so now she
can practice her Portuguese again now
one of the big events on Saint Patrick's
Day is the st. Patrick's Day parade in
every large city in America there is a
st. Patrick's Day parade there's an
expression in English don't rain on my
parade
this means I don't want you to spoil my
plans I don't want you to ruin my plans
by saying something or doing something
here are some common uses of this
expression I don't want to rain on your
parade but I'm sorry to rain on your
parade but I don't mean to rain on your
parade but example I don't want to rain
on your parade but you have no
experience in the restaurant business
how are you going to open and run a
restaurant all by yourself now one
reason I like Saint Patrick's Day is
because it's really the first spring
holiday I like it because March 17th
reminds us that spring is just around
the corner this expression means that
something is going to happen very soon
we expect it to happen very soon example
Francis's high school graduation is just
around the corner he's already excited
about starting college in the fall

summer vacation is just around the

Shannon received a very generous
